AGI -&nbsp;The spacecraft Blue Ghost has landed on the Moon to analyze the subsoil, surface and atmosphere of the satellite with ten instruments, within the Artemis programme of Nasa, which aims to establish a permanent human presence by the end of the decade. Among the various instruments on board, in all 10, there is also the so-called LuGre, Lunar GNSS Receiver Experiment, a receiver developed in Italy by Qascom> on behalf of the Italian Space Agency with the collaboration of NASA and the scientific support of the Politecnico di Torino. An hour before landing, the spacecraft performed an ignition of insertion into descent orbit, allowing a controlled approach to the landing site in the Sea Crisium, on the near side of the Moon.
After a trip lasted more than six weeks since its launch in Florida, which took place on January 15, > the lander of the American company Firefly Aerospace completed its final entry manoeuvre in the low lunar orbit on February 24. The ten instruments of Nasa on board the probe arrived in optimal conditions and are ready to study the properties of the lunar regolite, the geophysical characteristics and the interaction between the solar wind and the terrestrial magnetosphere.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The next days will be crucial for the Blue Ghost 1 mission, as the tools will collect valuable data on the lunar environment to open the way back to the moon and explore deep space.> The Italian LuGre, who has already managed to track the signals of the &nbsp;Global&nbsp;Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) at a record distance of 246,000 miles (about 400 kilometers) during his journey, demonstrating the feasibility of using terrestrial satellite constellations such as GPS and Galileo for navigation on the Moon, will try to establish a new record: the first reception of GNSS signals on the lunar surface.
On the other hand, the Lunar Environment Heliospheric X-ray Imager (LEXI) telescope is in operation shortly after the launch and accumulated more than 50 hours of operation for calibration and preparation. LEXI captures images of the interaction between Earth's magnetosphere and solar wind, providing valuable data on space meteorology. From the lunar surface will begin to collect data and fundamental images for scientific research. Among other instruments on board is the Regolith Adherence Characterization (RAC), which will assess how lunar powder adheres to different materials, crucial information for the design of future equipment and space suits.
The LISTER space probe (Lunar Instrumentation for Subsurface Thermal Exploration with Rapidity) will measure heat flow from the inside of the Moon, providing information about its thermal structure. With today's goal, Firefly Aerospace and Nasa have demonstrated an evolution of lunar landing technology > to open the way to future missions with crew and the sustained exploration of the Earth's natural satellite. The mission is also a step forward for NASA's Artemis program, aimed at ensuring a permanent presence on the Moon and fostering collaboration between public and private for space exploration. In total, the mission, part of NASA's Commercial Lunar Payload Services (CLPS) program, will last about 60 days, including transit on the Moon and operations on the lunar surface.
